{"type":"message","id":"9ada86a7","parentId":"0b190184","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:35:26.232Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_09nsumq545yt_2","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 113413\r\n\r\n## Applied Mutations\r\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\r\n\r\n\r\n## LLM Response\r\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nFrom the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n- CFI Analysis is complete (44.8% of frequency-invariants have CFI=0)\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n\r\nThe key insight from CFI analysis:\r\n- 44.8% are pure noise (CFI=0)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Need to distinguish between metaprogramming artifacts vs research trajectory\r\n\r\nWhat would advance the goals?\r\n1. Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n2. Design actual compression network\r\n3. CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe most impactful next step seems to be designing/implementing CFI-weighted compression. This is the natural next step after the CFI analysis.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete file edit I can make:\r\n- I could create a script for CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n- I could update the CFI_RESULTS.md with next steps\r\n- I could design the compression network spec\r\n\r\nGiven the stateless discontinuous nature and that we need concrete advancement, let me create a design/spec for the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would be a new file that outlines the experiment design.\r\n\r\nActually, let me check if there's already a compression-related file. The notes mention \"Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\" as pending.\r\n\r\nThe most concrete action would be to:\r\n1. Create a design/spec for the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nLet me draft this.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of frequency-invariants are pure noise (CFI=0), while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). This provides a clear filter criterion for compression - we should preferentially retain high-CFI invariants over frequency-only metrics.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a design document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment that will compare prediction quality using CFI-filtered invariants versus frequency-only baselines. This directly addresses the pending \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\" task.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-filtered compression (retain invariants with CFI >= 0.7) will yield superior next-pulse prediction compared to frequency-only compression (retain top-60 invariants by frequency).\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Only Compression\r\n- Take top-60 invariants by frequency from current corpus\r\n- Compress to fixed size N tokens\r\n- Use as context for next-pulse prediction\r\n- Measure: prediction accuracy on held-out session\r\n\r\n### Treatment: CFI-Weighted Compression\r\n- Filter invariants: CFI >= 0.7 (true causal anchors only)\r\n- Secondary sort: frequency among high-CFI invariants\r\n- Take top-60 by this metric\r\n- Compress to same N tokens\r\n- Use as context for next-pulse prediction\r\n- Measure: prediction accuracy on held-out session\r\n\r\n### Metrics to Compare\r\n1. Next-token prediction accuracy\r\n2. Concept drift detection rate\r\n3. Cross-session coherence score\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n- Frequency baseline retains ~5.7% high-CFI + ~94.3% noise artifacts\r\n- CFI-filtered retains ~100% high-CFI + 0% noise\r\n- Prediction quality gap reveals compression bottleneck location\r\n\r\n## Implementation Notes\r\n- CFI scores in: `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n- Invariant data: `research/frequency_analysis/invariants.csv`\r\n- Run on held-out session: `pulse_2026-03-24*.md`\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\r\n\r\n## For Next Instantiation\r\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\r\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:34:35"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1242,"aggregated":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 113413\r\n\r\n## Applied Mutations\r\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\r\n\r\n\r\n## LLM Response\r\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nFrom the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n- CFI Analysis is complete (44.8% of frequency-invariants have CFI=0)\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n\r\nThe key insight from CFI analysis:\r\n- 44.8% are pure noise (CFI=0)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Need to distinguish between metaprogramming artifacts vs research trajectory\r\n\r\nWhat would advance the goals?\r\n1. Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n2. Design actual compression network\r\n3. CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe most impactful next step seems to be designing/implementing CFI-weighted compression. This is the natural next step after the CFI analysis.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete file edit I can make:\r\n- I could create a script for CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n- I could update the CFI_RESULTS.md with next steps\r\n- I could design the compression network spec\r\n\r\nGiven the stateless discontinuous nature and that we need concrete advancement, let me create a design/spec for the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would be a new file that outlines the experiment design.\r\n\r\nActually, 